The senatorial order was now practically a hereditary nobility‚ consisting of those whose ancestors had held a curule magistracy, or who had themselves attained to that distinction. Any free-born citizen might be- come a candidate for office, but the opposition of the solid phalanx of the nobility made it very difficult for a new man (homo novus) to enter the political field. If he was elected to a curule office, however. he thereby ennobled his posterity. The members of the senatorial order were debarred from engag- ing in any trade or business. The badge of the senators was the tunic with a broad purple stripe (latus clavus).
